article.description: Diana Taurasi had 17 points and Anna Deforge added 16, as the Mercury beat the Lynx on Sunday night.
article.headline: Mercury tighten grip on playoff spot with win
article.linkText: Taurasi, Deforge lead Mercury past Lynx
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- If the Phoenix Mercury hang onto fourth place in
the Western Conference through the last week of the WNBA season,
they'll be in the playoffs.

Diana Taurasi had 17 points, five rebounds and two blocks, and
Anna Deforge added 16 points -- each in little more than one half of
play -- as the Mercury beat the Minnesota Lynx 83-69 on Sunday
night.

The loss -- Minnesota's third in four games to Phoenix --
eliminated the Lynx from postseason contention and preserved the
Mercury's one-game lead on Los Angeles with three to go.

"Right now, when you can get fresh legs for down the stretch
and get people into the game who haven't played all year, but do
really well, that gives our team a lot more confidence," Taurasi
said.

It was the third consecutive double-digit game for Taurasi, who
shot 6-of-11 from the field and 5-of-6 from the line while scoring
all of her points in the first half.

Reserve Sandora Irvin had 13 points and six rebounds for the
Mercury (16-15), and Kamila Vodichkova contributed 11 points and
five rebounds.

"We stayed focused, just working all night," Irvin said.
"It's a focus of our starters, just go out and give it their all,
try to get the score up high and then let us come in and continue
that."

Svetlana Abrosimova and Nicole Ohlde had 14 points each for the
Lynx (14-18).

The Mercury held a 42-24 lead at halftime, fueled by a 20-4 run
during which Taurasi scored seven points.

Abrosimova hit her first four shots during an 11-3 spurt by the
Lynx that got them to 45-35. But Phoenix answered with a 16-3 run
surge, with Vodichkova scoring seven points and DeForge adding five
as Phoenix took the suspense out of the game by building a 61-38
lead with 12:40 to play.

"They are playing very well right now," Lynx coach Suzie
McConnell Serio said. "They move the ball and have so many weapons
out there on the floor with their post players. We came out with
more energy (in the second half) and cut the lead down to 10, and
they came out of timeout and scored six straight times."
